               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>The <title xml:lang="ta">Alacammāṉai</title>. According to Vinson in Vinson et al. (1866-), this is the <title xml:lang="ta">Aṟ<ex>ciya</ex> Aṉacu Ammāṉai</title>, a poem in the <foreign xml:lang="ta">ammāṉai</foreign> genre praising Saint Anna, composed by the daughter of Ciṉṉatampimutaliyār of Santhome (Chennai).</p>
<p>According to the manuscript, the text was recited, and possibly also composed, by the daughter of <persName xml:lang="ta">Ciṉṉa Tampi Mutaliyār</persName>, named Viyākulam<sic>ma</sic>ḷ (U1, <locus facs="2">f[1]r, c2, line 3</locus>), Kula Ammāḷ (U1, <locus facs="2">f[1]r, c4, line 3-4</locus>), Ammaṇiyammāḷ viyākulam(U3, <locus facs="60">f54v, c2, line 3</locus>).</p> 
    <p>By a Christian copyist (see blessing), named Ārokkiyam (U3, <locus facs="60">f54v, c2, line 5</locus>).</p>

<p>Description based on the examination of the original manuscript (October 2021).</p>
<p>Dimensions assessed at the time of examination.</p>  
</summary>
                  
